<h2>One of Perl's biggest strengths is its community...</h2>
<table class="content_table">
    <tr>
        <td>
            <h4>
                Local Communities
            </h4>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.pm.org/">Perl Mongers</a> - find your local Perl group from over 300 groups world wide
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h4>
                Events
            </h4>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="/events.html">Events</a> - Perl conferences, hackathons and workshops and local groups around the world
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h4>
                Community Web Sites
            </h4>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.perl.org/">Perl.org</a> - You are here
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://blogs.perl.org/">blogs.perl.org</a> - Personal Perl blogs
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.perlmonks.com/">PerlMonks</a> - A community committed to sharing Perl knowledge and coding tips. The site contains questions and answers, useful snippets, and a library of code
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://ironman.enlightenedperl.org/">Planet Perl Iron Man</a> - open Perl blogging challenge
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://perlsphere.net/">Perlsphere</a> - another aggregation of selected Perl blogs
                </li>
            </ul>
            <h4>
                Mail Lists
            </h4>
            <p>
                <a href="http://lists.perl.org/">lists.perl.org</a> has information on all the Perl mailing lists you can join.  If you're just starting, you probably want to join <a href="http://learn.perl.org/faq/beginners.html">perl-beginners</a>.
            </p>
            
            
        </td>
        <td>
            <h4>
                Chat
            </h4>
            <p><a href="http://irchelp.org/irchelp/irctutorial.html">IRC</a> (Internet Relay Chat) enables communities to
               gather in 'channels' on-line and chat in real-time.  It's a great place
               to get help if you're polite and ask 
               <a href="http://catb.org/~esr/faqs/smart-questions.html">smart questions</a>.
               </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.irc.perl.org">irc.perl.org</a>
                </li>
            </ul>

            
            <h4>
                Organizations
            </h4>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.perlfoundation.org/">The Perl Foundation</a> 
                    - dedicated to the advancement of the Perl programming language through open discussion, collaboration, design, and code
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.enlightenedperl.org/">Enlightened Perl Organization</a> 
                    - a membership organization created to support the new wave of CPAN 
                    (Catalyst, DBIx::Class, Moose, etc.) and to evangelize the new 
                    Perl enlightenment
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.yapceurope.org/">YAPC Europe Foundation</a> - The YAPC::Europe Foundation (YEF) is a non-profit organization which works to promote Perl in Europe primarily through public events
                </li>
            </ul>
            
            <h4>
                Non-English Perl sites
            </h4>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <a href="http://www.perlfoundation.org/perl5/index.cgi?international_perl_resources">International Perl resources</a> - wiki with links to non-English Perl sites.
                </li>

            </ul>
            
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>




